				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/reuben-caldwell" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(4364608); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=4364608&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164196" alt="Reuben Caldwell" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=4364608)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/reuben-caldwell" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(4364608); return false;" >Reuben Caldwell</a></span> <span class="odate time_1541047592 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">01 Nov 2018 04:46</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4046275">
									

<p><strong>Warning potentially controversial idea coming</strong> I would be glad if became canon and SCP-096 was terminated for multiple reasons, which will be listed below;</p>
<ul>
<li>It's about time the Foundation was actually successful in killing a seemingly SCP like 096, it demonstrates a decent level of competence among them and how much they've progressed since they initially contained it.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Killing off a Series 1 vet may encourage others to pay more attention to the newer and lesser-known SCPs, broadening the community's horizons.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>SCP-173 assisting in the termination demonstrates its usefulness and explains why they haven't attempted to terminate it yet.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>SCP-096 is fairly overrated in my opinion, sure it's terrifying beyond belief, but it doesn't have much a backstory as far as I know and doesn't do much in the lore of the SCP universe.</li>
</ul>

							</div>

								
